※※
# scaffold-sky-workflow

Manually-run meta-workflow that authors a brand-new `.sky` workflow from a
plain-English brief, then lints it until it passes. Flow:

  (manual run: --var dir, name, request)
       │
       ▼
   ┌────────┐   writes from {{request}}   ┌──────────────────┐
   │ author │ ──────────────────────────▶ │ <dir>/<name>/workflow.sky │
   └────────┘   (sky-workflow-authoring)  └──────────────────┘
       │                                          ▲
       ▼                                          │ edits to fix errors
   ┌────────┐                                     │
   │  lint  │ ─── sky lint ──▶ errors? ──yes──▶ fix┘   (loop, max 6 passes)
   └────────┘                     │
                                  no (clean)
                                   │
                                   ▼
                                 done

Run it (you choose where the file lands with --var dir):

  sky run scaffold-sky-workflow \
    --var dir=".sky/workflows" \
    --var name="deploy-on-tag" \
    --var request="on a GitHub release, run the deploy script and post the result to Slack"

  - dir     directory the file is written to — STATE THIS before running (e.g. .sky/workflows)
  - name    kebab-case directory name (generates <dir>/<name>/workflow.sky)
  - request what the workflow should do, in plain English

Language: the brief in {{request}} may be in any language. The generated
workflow is always written in English (name, keys, node ids, prompt bodies);
only the ※※ comment blocks may be in the brief's language.

Required skill — install before first run (no marketplace plugin needed):

  sky library install sky-workflow-authoring
※※

⊕meta⊕
name = "scaffold-sky-workflow"
description = "Author a new .sky workflow from a plain-English brief and lint it until clean. Fire via: sky run scaffold-sky-workflow --var dir=<dir> --var name=<file> --var request=<what it should do>"
trigger.manual = true
output_style = "terse"
max_budget_usd = 2.00
⊕⊕

※※
Step 1 — author. Writes the new workflow file from the brief, following the
bundled sky-workflow-authoring skill (four delimiters, valid trigger, node DAG,
correct variable references). Does not lint yet — that's the next stage.
※※

§author§
model = "sonnet"
skills = ["sky-workflow-authoring"]
§§

∆author∆
Author a new Skylence `.sky` workflow at {{dir}}/{{name}}/workflow.sky.

What it must do: {{request}}

Language rule: the brief above may be written in any language. Write the workflow itself entirely in English — `name`, all config keys, node ids, and every ∆ prompt body. Only the ※※ comment blocks may be written in the brief's language, to document the workflow for its author.

Follow the sky-workflow-authoring skill exactly: the four Unicode delimiter blocks (⊕meta⊕, §id§, ∆id∆, ※※), `name = "{{name}}"` matching the filename, exactly one trigger, and a sensible node DAG. Pick node types (claude / bash / script / http / loop) that fit the brief. Two audiences (per the skill): write the ∆ prompt bodies for the model — terse, machine-oriented, no concern for human readability; write the ※※ comment blocks for the human — clear, and when the flow branches/loops/gates add the diagram that explains it fastest (ASCII, Mermaid, sequence, or swimlane). Create the {{dir}} directory if absent. Write the file — do not lint it yet.
∆∆

※※
Step 2 — lint. A loop node: each pass reads the file the author wrote, runs
`sky lint`, and fixes every reported error. The loop.until.bash condition
re-runs this node until lint exits 0 (max 6 passes). Loop nodes can't chain a
session, so the prompt reads the file fresh each pass.
※※

§lint§
model = "sonnet"
depends_on = ["author"]
skills = ["sky-workflow-authoring"]
loop.until.bash = "sky lint \"$SKY_DIR/$SKY_NAME/workflow.sky\""
loop.max = 6
§§

∆lint∆
Read {{dir}}/{{name}}/workflow.sky, then run `sky lint {{dir}}/{{name}}/workflow.sky` and read its output. Fix every reported error and warning in the file, using the sky-workflow-authoring skill's error-code table (SKY-WF-*) to map each code to its fix. Common ones: quote the RHS of `when`; add `chain_from` targets to `depends_on`; quote `$SKY_*` in bash; declare every env-var reference in the `secrets` array. Keep the workflow body in English. Re-run lint after editing. This node loops until lint passes — make concrete fixes each pass. When clean, output the final lint result and the file path.
∆∆
